<ns4888:section xmlns:ns4888="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.basicLanguage.codeBlocks">
    <ns4889:title xmlns:ns4889="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Blocks of Code</ns4889:title>
    <ns4890:para xmlns:ns4890="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">A block is delimited in Java by curly brackets. For example, the class definition is in a
        block. Similarly, the body of a method is enclosed within a block. You can add deeper nested
        blocks by adding further blocks of code enclosed within curly rackets. Usually this is done
        in the context of control statements like <ns4891:literal xmlns:ns4891="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">if</ns4891:literal> statements or
        <ns4892:literal xmlns:ns4892="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">while</ns4892:literal> loops to delimit in the first case a block of code which is
        executed only if a specified condition evaluates to <ns4893:literal xmlns:ns4893="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">true</ns4893:literal> and in the
        second case to enclose a block of code which is performed iteratively.</ns4890:para>
    <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" href="./codeBlocks/variableScope.docbook"/>
</ns4888:section>